From: Borislav Petkov <bp@suse.de>
Date: Tue May 14 10:43:46 CEST 2019
Subject: x86/MCE: Handle "nosmt" offlining properly
Patch-mainline: no, SUSE-specific
References: bsc#1134729

The "nosmt" boot cmdline parameter disables SMT siblings on a machine.
However, during boot, those SMT siblings need to be brought online once
so that CR4.MCE gets set (otherwise machine triple-faults on an MCE).

The old code sets up the per-CPU MCE timer in the CPU init path
mcheck_cpu_init() so when the sibling gets onlined, the timer is
started. That same timer is cancelled in the hotplug notifier, however.

cpu_up() which onlines the siblings, runs earlier than the MCE code and
thus there's no hotplug notifier registered yet, to cancel the timer
when the sibling is offlined immediately again in cpu_up().

So the timer remains running and fires on an offlined CPU after
the default interval of 5 minutes. Which triggers the WARN_ON() in
mce_timer_fn().

Instead of doing a major surgery on the CPU hotplug code, simply check
whether the CPU is online in the timer callback.

Reported-by: Michal Koutný <mkoutny@suse.com>
Signed-off-by: Borislav Petkov <bp@suse.de>

---
 arch/x86/kernel/cpu/mcheck/mce.c |    9 +++++++++
 1 file changed, 9 insertions(+)

--- a/arch/x86/kernel/cpu/mcheck/mce.c
+++ b/arch/x86/kernel/cpu/mcheck/mce.c
@@ -1315,6 +1315,15 @@ static void mce_timer_fn(unsigned long d
 	int cpu = smp_processor_id();
 	unsigned long iv;
 
+	/*
+	 * Return if the CPU has been offlined by "nosmt" or other similar
+	 * mitigation switches. The offlining happens before the CPU notifier is
+	 * registered so we cannot do proper cleanup like cancelling the timer.
+	 * So do the easy thing here. It also fixes a Xen issue, see bsc#929141.
+	 */
+	if (!cpu_online(data))
+		return;
+
 	WARN_ON(cpu != data);
 
 	iv = __this_cpu_read(mce_next_interval);
